article.headline: Comets to watch playoffs from home
article.linkText: Monarchs down Comets to tie for fourth in West
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- For the first time in franchise history, the
Houston Comets will not be part of the WNBA postseason.

Tangela Smith had 17 points and six rebounds for the Sacramento
Monarchs, who used a 12-0 run in the second half to eliminate the
Comets from playoff contention in the WNBA with a 71-62 victory
Thursday night.

The Comets had been to the playoffs every season since the
inception of the WNBA in 1997, and won the first four
championships.

The Monarchs moved into a tie with idle Phoenix for the fourth
and final playoff spot in the Western Conference. Both teams have
two games remaining.

Houston got 28 points from Tina Thompson but played most of the
game without forward Sheryl Swoopes, who sprained her left ankle.

"This was a hard one and we are just glad to get out of here
with a win," Monarchs head coach John Whisenant said. "I hated to
see Sheryl go down, she is a great player, but it certainly helped
the Monarchs with them losing one of their two big weapons.

"We knew that we were still going to have to stop Tina, so we
told everybody to get right up on her. That is the only way to stop
them."

Yolanda Griffith added 16 points for the Monarchs, who
eliminated the Comets from the playoffs a year ago. The Monarchs
had lost three in a row on the road before winning Thursday night.

"I think are chances of making the playoffs right now are very
good," Smith said. "We still feel like we have to win each of our
last two games, but we certainly control our own destiny."

Sacramento will finish up the regular season with a pair of home
games. The Monarchs host Houston in a rematch on Saturday before
playing Minnesota on Sunday in Sacramento.

Houston led 35-33 at halftime, and extended its advantage when
Thompson hit a 3-pointer 1:03 into the second half. But the
Monarchs countered with their decisive run.

"We just started pushing the ball after they took that lead,"
Smith said. "We knew we were going to have to run a little more
and get the offensive rebounds. After that, all we had to do was
get the ball inside and we did."

The Monarchs took an 8-2 lead before the teams traded baskets
for most of the first half.

Trailing 17-12, the Comets responded with a 10-4 run to take a
22-21 lead with 7:50 left in the half. Thompson led the Comets with
14 first-half points and Smith had 10 for Sacramento.

"I thought Tina Thompson gave a Super Woman-like effort
tonight," Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "I thought she did
some things that I thought were just unbelievable.

"Sacramento just played so well and it is just hard to play as
hard as we did when they played as well as they did. We just had
trouble finding some other people to help us score tonight."
